# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1904-new-york-giants-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The **1878 Boston Red Caps season** was the eighth season of the franchise.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps won their second straight National League pennant.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1879-providence-grays-season] The **1879 Providence Grays** won the National League title in only their second season in the league.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1880 Chicago White Stockings season** was the ninth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the fifth in the National League and the third at Lakefront Park.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 67–17.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1881 Chicago White Stockings season** was the tenth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the sixth in the National League and the fourth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 56–28.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1882 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 11th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the seventh in the National League and the fifth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 55–29, 3 games ahead of the second place Providence Grays.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1904-new-york-giants-season] The **1904 New York Giants season** was the 22nd season in franchise history.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1904-new-york-giants-season] They led the National League in both runs scored and fewest runs allowed, on their way to 106 wins and the pennant.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1904-new-york-giants-season] The first modern World Series had been played the previous year, but manager John McGraw and owner John T.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1904-new-york-giants-season] Brush refused to play the American League champion Boston Americans in a World Series.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1904-new-york-giants-season] They would change their position the following year.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1904-new-york-giants-season] The Giants had little offensive firepower in this pitching-dominated era but scored using a balanced lineup and a lot of small-ball tactics formerly employed by manager McGraw in his playing days.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1904-new-york-giants-season] The lineup featured three of the top five stolen base leaders in the majors: Bill Dahlen, Sam Mertes, and Dan McGann.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1904-new-york-giants-season] They also had one of the greatest pitching duos of all-time in Joe McGinnity and Christy Mathewson.
[src:1904-new-york-giants-season/1904-new-york-giants-season] They combined for 68 wins – a 20th-century record for two pitchers on the same team.
